A tall structure, equipped for loading, unloading, processing and storing grain.

A man-made heap of mining or quarrying products excluding waste materials.  (See also AB000)
Hill of refuse from a mine, industrial plant, etc. on land.
Justification:
To permit mapping S-57 attribute CATPRA.  This S-57 value specifically represents a single, individual refuse pile which may be easily and quickly recognized when used as a reference for navigation.   
AB000 US-Disposal Site/Waste Pile UK-Refuse Tip/Slag Heap won't work as it is defined as an area and not a point.  
AM040 US-Mineral Pile UK-Mineral Pile/Mineral Tip won't work as its definition specifically excludes waste material.
UK:  DISCUSS NO  Problem appreciated, but consider removing the “area” restriction from AB000 instead.  UK would use AB000 anyway, and let the product indicate whether it is area or point.  A point is still an area at a larger scale.  Given the “land restriction proposed for AM041, there is am implied mixed concept in AB000 for which the UK names would only apply to land use, but maybe the US name could apply to water use.  The definition makes no restriction.  
CZ: 
     a) The definition generally should not limit the geometric type except where the feature really can not be anything else at any resolution or scale. e.g. trigonometric point cannot be nothing but point.
     b) It is impossible to say what is waste and what is raw material. What is waste for you today can be a raw material for me tomorrow. The material should be simply an attribute not part of feature definition.
US:  YES  This is a new addition to S-57 for Edition 3.1.  This solution was suggested because we need a feature to represent a new type of conspicuous landmark used as a reference for marine navigation, a single refuse pile.  The US and CA when working this issue in May, labored under the understanding that the FACC WP would not entertain any changes to definitions which would fundamentally alter the object such as removing the word "area".  I (Buckley) would really prefer to reword AB000, perhaps replacing "Area" with "Site" or something similar, but I don't see how we can handle both the mandate that the refuse be in only one pile (not many piles) and that it exclude a refuse pile in the water.  This feature needs to be compatible with the S-57 definition for  ENC to DNC conversions.  
If this feature is not approved the US will turn it into a US national code and  those nations  working with both DNCs and ENCs will then need to share a US national code with no input into the configuration control.  This is a situation I would at all costs prefer to avoid.  If only one nation will ever use it, then it probably should be a national code, however in this case several nations will ultimately be using and sharing it.  For that reason alone, it belongs in FACC.
GE:  NO The justification is not sound. First, it is a question of scale, and second AB000 is not defined as an „area feature“. That would not be possible due to the rule „...should not specify if the feature is an area, point or line feature“.
IT:   NO  According with the rules FACC should not specify if the feature is an area, point or line feature.  On IT understanding the AB000 definition does not give any feature type restriction (point, area or line feature).
US:  Withdrawn since mods made to AB000 eliminate need for this feature..

Comments:
Definition needs to be massaged to differentiate a groin from a breakwater. BE 
Agree Buckley US
Groins are normally constructed perpendicular to a beach, not a harbor or anchorage. They are intended to preserve the beach by preventing the longshore movement of sediments by disrupting the longshore transport mechanisms.  
A breakwater normally is constructed parallel to or at a low angle to the coastline and is intended to protect a harbor or anchorage from waves, wind, and high seas.  Effects on sediment transport are only an incidental side effect which may or may not be deliberate.  Buckley US
IT concurs, keep BB040 for backward compatibility.

FAC_NAME: Large Isolated Rock, Boulder, or Rocky Formation
FAC_DESCRIPTION: A conspicuous  isolated rocky formation or single large stone existing in its entirety above the high water mark.  From offshore it would appear to a mariner as a single point on land and would be appropriate for use in navigation.
Change History: Version 2.1: New Feature to permit mapping of S-57
Justification: To permit mapping S-57 attribute CATLMK.
Comments:
GE:  NO  1) Has concerns about the use of scale or product dependent words such as 'isolated'.
         2) Depends on the scale as well. And : Conflict with DB160 Rock Strata /Rock Formation.
BE:  An isolated rock and an isolated rocky formation are not necessarily the same thing.
UK:  This conflict will be common when we are mapping to a catalog having a 'higher authority' such as IHO.
ALL: Keep as generic as possible to allow maximum scope for use.
US:  In using the IHO definition, we are being less restrictive however I have changed the feature name to reflect the full scope of the attribute.
UK:  Still thinking!!  FWP6 had a problem with this. Concerned about mixed concepts, confusion with DB160, and meaning of “isolated”   ??????????
CZ:  "Isolated" seems to be clear, I understand it as an opposite to connected here. I don't see any scale dependency in it.  FACC deals with real world features, not with maps.
US:  YES
The fundamental purpose of this new feature is to support a mariner looking for conspicuous landmarks to use in fixing his position.  A rock or boulder in a talus slope amongst many others is not conspicuous, one standing alone on a hillside is.  The same goes for a rock outcrop.  In many parts of the world, especially with a paucity of conspicuous landmarks, rocks and outcrops are frequently charted to be used by the mariner as landmarks.  The scale of reference is the mariner's view.  If it can be portrayed as a single object and if the mariner can quickly recognize it with no doubt of it being confused with others, then it belongs here.
IT:  NO  Seems to be in conflict with DB160.  However, needs further discussion!

FAC_DESCRIPTION: An inclined plane, symmetrical about the runway centerline, beginning 200 feet outboard of the runway end point, at the height of the runway end point and extending for 42332 feet (7nm - 200 feet of primary surface). The slope of the approach clearance surface is 50 to 1 along the runway centerline extended until it reaches a height of 500 feet above the height of the lowest runway end on the airport. It then continues horizontally at this height to a point 42532 feet (7nm) from the end of the runway. The width of this surface at the runway end is the same as the primary surface, it flares uniformly, and the width at 42,532 feet is 13,899 feet.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: This surface connects the side of the runway primary and approach surfaces to the inner horizontal surface.  The surface extends outward, perpendicular to the centerline of each runway, from the edges of the primary surface, at a slope of 7:1 to a width of 1050 feet and a height of 150 feet above the lowest runway end.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: The inner horizontal surface for each runway is defined by two half circles centered on the runway ends and joined by tangents.  The radii of the half circles are 7500 feet and the tangents are parallel to the runway centerline at a distance of 7500 feet.  The surface is a constant 150 feet above the lowest runway end.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: A surface extending from the periphery of the inner horizontal surface outward and upward at a slope of 20:1 for a horizontal distance of 7000 feet to a height of 500 feet above the lowest runway end.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: A plane, located 500 feet above the lowest runway end, extending outward from the outer periphery of the conical surface for a horizontal distance of 28032 feet.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: This surface connects the side of the approach surface to the conical and outer horizontal surface.  The surface extends outward, perpendicular to the extended runway centerline from the edges of the approach surface, at a 7:1 slope.   The slope of the 7:1 surface is referenced to the runway centerline.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: Adjacent area along either side of a road or runway not normally used by vehicles or aircraft, but provided as an allowable margin in case of emergency situations.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: The point on a line that is nearest to an off line point.  For example, a point on the runway centerline is “abeam” the Glide Slope Antenna when the distance from the centerline point to the antenna is a minimum.
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: The highest point of an airport’s usable runways measured in feet from the geoid (orthometric height).
Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: A device, normally placed near the threshold of a runway, used for reflecting radar signals.

A designated portion of water outlined by visual surface markings, used by seaplanes to land and take off.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: A prepared surface providing access to/from runways and the aircraft parking area, terminal area, or service area, etc.

Justification: Airfield Initiative requirement.

IT: ???   It is not clear the given justification. Need further discussion.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: A monumented or unmonumented point which serves as a  point on and which partially defines a segment of a national boundary baseline.  This baseline is used for defining the landward edge or margin of a nation's various contiguous zones such as the 3 and 12 nautical mile limits and the Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ).
Justification: Recent boundaries modelling discovered that this concept was missing from the available options in FACC.  Baseline Points don't always have a physical monument associated with them, therefore the use of ZB030 US-Boundary Monument  UK-Boundary Monument/Boundary Mark would be inappropriate.  Baseline Points are always associated with baselines,  therefore the use of  ZB035 Control Point/Control Station would also be inappropriate.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: An object or mark on the ground of known position, elevation, or both.
Justification: There is a requirement to include both temporary and permanent marks under this feature.  Currently only temporary marks are allowed.  This change involves an expansion of the definition, making it less restrictive not more restrictive.

FAC_DESCRIPTION: Place Holder - ZE
A generic area to which metadata attributes apply and which is not covered by any other feature code.  (See also ZM002 - ZM014)
Justification: There are S-57 metadata attributes which apply not to a particular feature but rather to a specific geographic region.  Therefore a generic "Meta Object", to use the S-57 terminology, is needed to support these attributes.
Comments:
UK: Still thinking about metadata objects in general!  ??????????
CZ: Should "metadata features" be mixed with real world features in FACC? Let's have in mind the goals of FACC (DIGEST Part 1)  Metadata should be metadata (or exceptionally attributes) but not features.  
What about consulting with the Metadata WG and ISO/TC 211 Geographic information - Part 15: Metadata?
US: The idea behind adding metadata features was to provide an area delineation within the datasets of where a particular metadata attribute applies and is constant.  Currently we can only apply metadata characteristics to an entire coverage/library (normally in the DQ layer).  What if the nature of the metadata changes within the same layer/coverage?  This solution was thought better than adding a suite of metadata attributes to each and every feature within the library.   As for the Metadata working group coming up with something - they passed it back to us to find a solution.
GE: ???  (Still thinking). It should be taken into consideration that this new subcategory includes features that do not fit in with the FACC landscape at all („FACC provides a means for encoding real world entities or objects for the purpose of an orderly exchange of digital geospatial information between organizations“).  We suggest to retain the S-57 terminology and call the new sub-category „meta objects“ rather than „meta data“.
IT:  NO  IT opinion is that Metadata features do not belong to FACC which “..provide means for encoding real world entities or objects..”. It could be a good idea consult with Metadata WG and ISO/TC211 Geographic Information - Part 15 Metadata.
